-- Hong Kong shares rise robustly on signs of market stability 
-- By Shanghai Newsroom
-- Mon Dec 22, 2014 03:05AM EST
-- None



HONG KONG, Dec 22 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares produced solid gains on Monday, underpinned by gains in mainland markets plus stability in crude oil prices and the Russian ruble.

The H-share index far outperformed the Hang Seng index as Chinese energy conglomerates listed in Hong Kong rises. The Hang Seng index <.HSI> rose 1.3 percent, to 23,408.57 points, while the China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> gained 3.0 percent, to 11,744.02 points. Among the most actively traded stocks on Hong Kong's main board were Alibaba Pictures Group Ltd <1060.HK>, down 3.1 percent at HK$1.56  Bank Of China <3988.HK>, up 3.8 percent at HK$4.33 and CCT Land Holdings Ltd <0261.HK>, down 5.3 percent at HK$0.02. Chinese investment flowing from Shanghai into Hong Kong through the mutual market access pilot programme took up 0.37 billion yuan ($59.50 million) of the 10.5 billion yuan daily quota <.SQUOTA.HS>.